## What happened

`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. DSA was marked obsolete in .NET 7 (`SYSLIB0028`), and Apple's Security.framework never provided native DSA support. In earlier .NET versions, the runtime fell back to an OpenSSL-based implementation on macOS, but .NET 11 removed that fallback, making DSA unavailable on the platform entirely.

## How to fix it

Since you only need **verification** of legacy signatures (not new signing), the cleanest fix is to use a managed (pure C#) DSA implementation that doesn't depend on the OS crypto stack:

**Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended)**

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DSAParameters dsaParams)
{
    var p = new DsaParameters(
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.P),
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.Q),
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.G));

    var pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(
        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, dsaParams.Y), p);

    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA-1withDSA");
    verifier.Init(false, pubKey);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

**Option 2 – Guard with a runtime check** (if you can skip macOS)

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // ...
}
```

**Recommendation:** Go with BouncyCastle — it's a managed implementation that works identically on all platforms, avoids the `SYSLIB0028` obsolete warning, and keeps your library cross-platform without OS crypto dependencies.
